    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-10T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-10T13:00:00-05:00" n="630"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d630">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">835.24/2396: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-10T15:00:00-03:00"
                            >December 10, 1943—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 8:26 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>5662. Aranha<note n="70" xml:id="d630fn70">Oswaldo Aranha, Brazilian Minister for
                        Foreign Affairs.</note> showed me a telegram from Rodrigues Alves<note
                        n="71" xml:id="d630fn71">Brazilian Ambassador in Argentina.</note> again
                    urging that Moreira da Silva<note n="72" xml:id="d630fn72">Onetime Brazilian
                        Minister of Finance.</note> be allowed to give Argentina <pb facs="0696"
                        n="684" xml:id="pg_684"/> some rubber, insisting that if this were not done
                    the negotiations would result in complete failure; and that if this were done
                    Argentina would grant additional facilities for the importation of Brazilian
                    textiles, et cetera. He referred again also to the frozen credit situation. He
                    spoke of loss of Brazilian prestige, danger of unfavorable reaction on the
                    Argentine military, et cetera, if the negotiations collapsed.</p>
                <p>Aranha remarked “You will note that Rodrigues Alves is very insistent about the
                    rubber. I am still telling him no; but I would like to observe that the United
                    States and Great Britain both find it necessary to continue to make considerable
                    purchases in the Argentine; we find it necessary to make purchases there
                    too”.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Buenos Aires.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
